        "Description/Abstract": "In recent years, correctional agencies have increased their use of inmate video visitation (IVV) in an effort to offset costs and increase security, among other objectives. In the present study, interviews and surveys were conducted with inmates at a jail in the Northwestern U.S. that had replaced in-person, glass partition visitation with IVV. The results suggested that while there were positive aspects of IVV, such as the ability to visit with loved ones from afar, there were criticisms as well, including technological and access issues. The policy implications of the findings and directions for future research on IVV are discussed.",
